<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-frustums" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Frustums</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction component="lesson-plan">
            <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a frustum as the shape formed when a cone or pyramid is cut parallel to its base, removing the top portion. Identify the properties: two circular bases, slant height, and height. State the formula: Total Surface Area <m>= \pi(R + r)\ell + \pi R^2 + \pi r^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the total surface area of frustums using the formula. Find slant heights using the Pythagorean theorem. Use similarity to determine missing dimensions of a frustum.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving frustum surface areas such as buckets, lampshades, cups, and cooling towers. Determine material requirements for frustum-shaped objects.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-of-frustums.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-of-frustums.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups of 3–4
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Activity:</alert> Modelling a Frustum Using Paper Cups or Cone Nets
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p><q>What is a frustum?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>What happens when you cut the top part of a cone parallel to the base?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>What surfaces make up a frustum?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>What would happen to the surface area if the top radius increased?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>Why is it necessary to measure the slant height, not the vertical height?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>Can you find any real-life objects shaped like a frustum?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to cut and assemble the frustum.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask probing questions: <q>What surfaces do you see? How can we find the area of each surface?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For struggling groups: <q>Let us start by finding the area of the bottom base. Then find the area of the top base. What about the curved surface?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For early finishers: <q>Given a full cone, how much surface area is lost when the top is cut off?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>



    <activity xml:id="auto_oecrrf2w">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_m5bxed8d">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gak37leu">
              Modelling a frustum using a paper cup or cone-shaped fruit juice glass and calculate its surface area.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3yvlurb6">
                <m>\textbf{ Materials needed:}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bjv9hzkz">
                <ul xml:id="auto_s1crebpj">
                    <li xml:id="auto_d4e55sxu">
                        <p xml:id="auto_rci9wau8">
                           Printable nets of a cone (to cut and create a frustum)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_7dhhugds">
                            🔹 Rulers or measuring tape
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_j7m2t4kl">
                            🔹 Scissors

                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_201zpzzk">
                            
                            🔹 Tape or glue
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_p3mvuher">
                           🔹  Formula sheet
                         </p>
                         <p xml:id="auto_6x8932av">
                            🔹 Worksheets for sketching and calculations 
                         </p>
                       
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ojzzvowc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bdxqvqg1">
                            A  frustum is formed when the top part of a cone is cut off parallel to the base.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_upg6vkma">
                        <p xml:id="auto_axmdoia5">
                            Surface area includes:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ypgfetz1">
                          🔹 <m>\textbf{Curved surface area}</m> (side)
                         </p> 
                         <p xml:id="auto_28xy0nfd"> 
                          🔹 <m>\textbf{Area of both circular bases}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tohzztkc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_watu4x1q">
                             Build the Frustum Model.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_51gng2v7">
                            🔹 Take the cone net and cut off the top part (smaller cone) parallel to the base.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_mjc7572b">
                           🔹  Assemble the remaining portion to form a frustum
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_416tkh7g">
                         🔹 Alternatively, use actual paper/plastic cups and measure directly
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_11n70cn6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_wqkr5aew">
                             Label Dimensions
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_u34tvhly">
                            🔹 Radius of the larger base (R)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_z1h7uy49">    
                            🔹 Radius of the smaller top base (r)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_73eikfrz">    

                           🔹  Slant height (l) of the frustum
                        </p>   
                        <p xml:id="auto_xytm50cj"> 
                            🔹 (If not provided, measure the height and use the Pythagorean theorem)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xu7t3fa8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_miftf093">
                            Calculate Surface Area
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_u94z45r4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0dx29v6d">
                           🔹  Use the surface area formula:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_m4m9xuut">
                            🔹 Total Surface Area = <m>\pi (R+r)\ell + \pi R^2 + \pi r^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_pypvi57r">
                        <p xml:id="auto_9r3a64me">
                           🔹  <m>\pi(R+r)</m>l: Curved surface
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_y52196nf">
                           🔹 <m> \pi R^2</m>: Area of bottom base
                         
                            </p>
                         <p xml:id="auto_jlbppa4l">
                          🔹 <m>\pi r^2</m>: Area of top base
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_vyxsl2nl">
                        <p xml:id="auto_sd9leb2p">
                            Example: Given Top radius (r): 3 cm , Bottom radius (R): 5 cm and Slant height (l): 6 cm
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_j8fzdvxv">

                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Surface Area } =\amp \pi(5\, \text {cm}+3\, \text {cm})(6\, \text {cm}) + \pi(5\, \text {cm})^2 + \pi(3\, \text {cm})^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp  3.14 \times (8\, \text {cm})\times(6\, \text {cm}) + 3.14 \times 25\, \text {cm} + 3.14 \times 9\, \text {cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp (3.14 \times \, 48 \text {cm} ) \times(3.14 \times \, 25 \text {cm} )  \times(3.14 \times \, 9 \text {cm} )  </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 150.72 \, \text{cm}^2 + 78.50 \, \text{cm}^2 + 28.26\, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp257.48\, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_d80v2tjq">
                        <p xml:id="auto_gb60m00i">
                            <m>\textbf{Study Questions}.</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_0uhan0yk">
                            🔹 What would happen to the surface area if the top radius increased?
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ydoz8oi0">
                           🔹 Why is it necessary to measure the slant height, not the vertical height?
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_p5spt2l4">
                           🔹 Can you find any real-life objects shaped like a frustum?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_v28wglhg">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ek8ds4sd">
                            <m>\textbf{Assignment}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_8t4c0udn">
                            Design their own frustum cups with chosen dimensions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_trw9ckpm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_uaarmssx">
                            Given a full cone, how much surface area is “lost” when the top is cut off?
                        </p>
                    </li>
    
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>

    </activity>

    <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_t2r3m5af">
            A frustum is a cone or pyramid is cut parallel to its base, removing the top portion. This results in a truncated shape with two parallel bases one smaller than the other e.g a lampshades, Truncated cones in engineering, buckets, Tunnels, Cooling towers in power plants etc
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vimjgh2r">
            <ul xml:id="auto_1o1wckou">
                <li xml:id="auto_6mibtwxg">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3qg346u9">
                        Thereby a frustum is the portion of a cone (or pyramid) that remains after the top part is cut off parallel to the base.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_25nnvmxq">
                        <m>\textbf{Properties of a Frustum}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_i7lwdj43">
                    <p xml:id="auto_t0ftonj2">
                        Two Circular Bases - A frustum has a larger base and a smaller base (both circular).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w4ku90lv">
                    <p xml:id="auto_73y57b2f">
                    Slant Height <m>\ell</m>. The distance between the two bases along the side of the frustum. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_h0431rac">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tp2btpkf">
                        Height <m>h</m> - The vertical distance between the two bases.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uzs39hbu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_n9u8u11s">
                        Curved Surface Area (CSA) - The side surface that connects the two bases.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2x651fng">
                    <p xml:id="auto_oaedynaw">
                        Total Surface Area (TSA) - The sum of the CSA and the areas of the two circular bases.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3e0k4bft">
                    <p xml:id="auto_z3uqppld">
                        <m>\textbf{NOTE:}</m> Volume, the space inside the frustum, is calculated using a formula derived from a full cone.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_n0g1wrua">
            <m>\textbf{Types of frustums}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gd9z6pua">
        <m>\textbf{Full cone}</m> 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3dr7l1t4">
            Important formulas to note;
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_50k7uswf">
            <ol xml:id="auto_ahufmt28">
                <li xml:id="auto_01p9hcpw">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6b7q7ias">
                        Slant Height <m>\ell</m>
                        <me>
                            \ell = \sqrt{(H+h)^2 + R^2}
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0m2rt2or">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ao26trhs">
                        Curved Surface Area (CSA)
                        <me>
                            CSA = \pi\, RL  \,\text{and}  \pi\, rl \, \text{for the smaller cone}
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dbwfo1s5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_by2tzvlb">
                        3. Total Surface Area (TSA)
                        <me>
                            \pi RL + \pi rl
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Whole class
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalise the formula for finding the surface area of a frustum. Direct learners' attention to the Key Takeaway box above.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Prompting Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p><q>What is the difference between a frustum and a cone?</q></p></li>
                <li><p><q>Do I only need the curved surface area?</q> (No — you must add both circular bases.)</p></li>
                <li><p><q>Are the slant height and vertical height the same?</q> (No — the slant height is along the side.)</p></li>
                <li><p><q>Can I use the cone formula directly for a frustum?</q> (No — a frustum has two bases.)</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_214uny0x">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual, then pairs to compare
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Walk learners through the worked examples that follow. The first example uses similarity to complete a cone before calculating. Encourage learners to attempt the second example independently before revealing the solution.
        </p>
    </axiom>

          <example xml:id="auto_vx4a9xrm">
        <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_dxoz8g3r">
                    Find the surface area of the galvanized iron bucket below.
                </p>
             <image width="40%">
        <latex-image label="frustum-galvanised-iron-bucket">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                  % Define a light purple color
                    \definecolor{lightpurple}{RGB}{230,230,250}
                    
                    % Bottom ellipse (full width)
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (4 and 2);
                    \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,0) ellipse (4 and 2);
                    
                    % Top ellipse (narrower)
                    \draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (2 and 1);
                    \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,5) ellipse (2 and 1);
                    
                    % Side surfaces
                    \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.5] 
                        (-4,0) -- (-2,5) -- (2,5) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Outline of side lines
                    \draw[thick] (-4,0) -- (-2,5);
                    \draw[thick] (4,0) -- (2,5);
                    \draw[thick] (-4,0) -- (4,0);
                    \draw[thick] (-2,5) -- (2,5);
                    
                    % Height line (dashed)
                    \draw[dashed, blue] (0,0) -- (0,5);
                    
                    % Dimension lines and labels
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-4.5,0) -- node[left] {20 cm} (-4.5,5);
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-4.2,0) -- node[below] {40 cm} (4.2,0);
    
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
             </statement>
             <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_ck2kgyqz">
                    Complete the cone from which the bucket is made, by adding a smaller cone of height <m>x </m>cm.
                </p>
                              <image width="40%">

                <latex-image label="galvanised-frustum">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define a light purple color
                        \definecolor{lightpurple}{RGB}{230,230,250}
                        
                        % Bottom ellipse (wider)
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
                        \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
                        
                        % Top ellipse (narrower)
                        \draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (1.5 and 0.75);
                        \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,5) ellipse (1.5 and 0.75);
                        
                        % Side surfaces
                        \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.5] 
                            (-3,0) -- (-1.5,5) -- (1.5,5) -- (3,0) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Outline of side lines
                        \draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (-1.5,5);
                        \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (1.5,5);
                        \draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
                        \draw[thick] (-1.5,5) -- (1.5,5);
                        \draw[dashed] (-1.5,5) --(0,8);
                        \draw[dashed] (1.5,5) --(0,8);
                        \draw[dashed] (0,5) --(0,8);                       
                        % Height line (dashed)
                        \draw[dashed, blue] (0,0) -- (0,8);
                        <!-- \draw[circle] (8.0); -->
                        % Dimension lines and labels
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3.5,0) -- node[left] {20 cm} (-3.5,5);
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3,0) -- node[below] {40 cm} (3,0);
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (2,5) -- node[left] {x cm} (2,8);
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-1.5,5) -- node[above] {30 cm} (1.5,5);

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_vs33sglp">
                    From the cocept of similarity and enlargement;
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ax6rl18f">
                    <m>\frac{R}{r} = \frac{H}{h}</m> and <m>\frac{H-h}{R-r} = \frac{h}{r}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ysbe0wal">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{x}{15} = \amp\frac {x + 20 \text{cm} }{20 \text{cm}}</mrow>
                        <mrow> 20 x  = \amp 15x \text{cm} + 300 \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow>300 \text{cm} = \amp  20 x -  15 x  </mrow>
                        <mrow> 300 \text{cm} = \amp 5x</mrow>
                        <mrow>60 \text{cm} = \amp x</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ll0potfh">
                    Surface area of a frustrum = Area of curved surface of bigger cone - Area of curved surface of snaller cone
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_fdszqrx0">
                    <m>\pi RL - \pi rl</m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Surface area (Large)} = \amp \frac {22}{7} \times 20 \text{cm} \times \sqrt{80^2 + 20^2} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 5183.33 \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{Surface area (small)} = \amp \frac {22}{7} \times 15 \text{cm} \times \sqrt{60^2 + 15^2} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 2915.62 \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Differences in the Surface areas} = \amp 5183.33 \text{cm} - 2915.62 \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 2267.71 \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
             </solution>
             </example>

             <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A bucket is in the shape of a frustum of a cone. The top radius is 
                        <m>14</m> cm, the bottom radius is <m>6</m> cm, and the vertical 
                        height of the bucket is <m>24</m> cm.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Find the total surface area of the bucket (Take <m>\pi = 3.142</m>). 
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="Step 1:">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use similarity to find the heights of the two cones.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Let the height of the large cone be <m>H</m> and the height of the small cone be <m>h</m>.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    From similarity:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\frac{H}{h} = \frac{R}{r}\amp </mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{14}{6}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{7}{3}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    So, <m>H = \frac{7}{3}h</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Since the frustum height is 24 cm:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>H - h = 24</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{7}{3}h - h = 24</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{4}{3}h = 24</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>h = 18 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Therefore: <m>H = 42 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                   Find slant heights. 
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Large cone:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> L = \amp \sqrt{42^2 + 14^2}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{1764 + 196}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{1960}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp 44.29 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Small cone:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> l = \amp \sqrt{18^2 + 6^2}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{324 + 36}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{360}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp 18.97 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Curved surface areas.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Large cone:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                   <m>\pi R L = 3.142 \times 14 \times 44.29 = 1948.7 \;\text{ cm}^2</m> 
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                   Small cone: 
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\pi r l = 3.142 \times 6 \times 18.97 = 357.6 \text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Curved surface area of frustum:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>1948.7 - 357.6 = 1591.1 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Add area of the base.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\pi r^2 = 3.142 \times 6^2 = 113.1 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Total Surface Area:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>1591.1 + 113.1 = 1704.2 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </solution>
             </example>

             <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A container is in the shape of a frustum of a rectangular pyramid. The bottom base measures <m>20 \text{ cm} \times 12 \text{ cm}</m>, the top base measures <m>10 \text{ cm} \times 6 \text{ cm}</m>, and the vertical height is <m>15 \text{ cm}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Find the total surface area of the frustum.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="Step 1:">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find the slant heights.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Difference in lengths:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{20 - 10}{2} = 5 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Slant height (length direction):
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                   <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Slant height (length direction)} = \amp \sqrt{15^2 + 5^2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{225 + 25}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{250}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp 15.81 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                   </md>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Difference in widths:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{12 - 6}{2} = 3 \text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Slant height (width direction)} = \amp \sqrt{15^2 + 3^2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{225 + 9}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{234}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp 15.33 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find areas of trapezoidal faces. Two faces with parallel sides 20 cm and 10 cm:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{1}{2}(20 + 10)(15.81) = 237.15 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Total for both is <m>2 \times 237.15 = 474.3 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Two faces with parallel sides 12 cm and 6 cm:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{1}{2}(12 + 6)(15.33) = 137.97 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Total for both is <m>2 \times 137.97 = 275.94 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Add base areas.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Bottom base area is <m>20 \times 12 = 240 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Top base area is <m>10 \times 6 = 60 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Total Surface Area.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>474.3 + 275.94 + 240 + 60 = 1050.24 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </solution>
             </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Exit Ticket:</alert> Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>A frustum of a square pyramid has top side length <m>4</m> m, bottom side length <m>6</m> m, and slant height <m>5</m> m. Calculate the total surface area.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>A conical frustum has a bottom radius of <m>6</m> cm and a slant height of <m>10</m> cm. (i) Explain the difference between curved surface area and total surface area. (ii) Find only the curved surface area.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>If the curved surface area of a frustum is <m>330 \text{ cm}^2</m>, the top radius is <m>5</m> cm, and the bottom radius is <m>10</m> cm, find the slant height.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>Lateral <m>= \frac{1}{2}(16 + 24) \times 5 = 100 \text{ m}^2</m>. Base areas <m>= 16 + 36 = 52 \text{ m}^2</m>. Total <m>= 152 \text{ m}^2</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>(i) CSA is only the side surface; TSA includes CSA plus both circular bases. (ii) CSA <m>= \pi \times 6 \times 10 = 188.50 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><m>330 = 3.14 \times (10 + 5) \times \ell</m>, so <m>\ell = 330 \div 47.1 = 7</m> cm.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

             <p xml:id="auto_4leeirc1">
