    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Provide pre-cut frustum models for students to measure.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use frustums with simple dimensions for initial practice.</p></li>
                <li><p>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li><p>Break down the formula into steps: find bottom base area, find top base area, find curved surface area, add.</p></li>
                <li><p>Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to verify their formula with different frustum dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with frustums with and without top bases.</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge students to find the surface area when only height and radii are given.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Challenge students to derive the formula using similarity and enlargement.</p></li>
                <li><p>Explore real-world applications: lampshades, buckets, cooling towers, tunnels.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate problems where the slant height must be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem.</p></li>
                <li><p>Apply the concept to composite solids involving frustums.</p></li>
                <li><p>Solve optimisation problems: given a fixed surface area, what dimensions maximise the volume?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Real-World Application: Designing Frustum Cups</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Work in groups. Design your own frustum cups with chosen dimensions for a school event.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li><p>Choose dimensions for your frustum cup (top radius, bottom radius, slant height).</p></li>
                <li><p>Calculate the surface area of your cup using the frustum formula.</p></li>
                <li><p>Determine how much material (paper or plastic) is needed to make 100 cups.</p></li>
                <li><p>If material costs Ksh 2 per square cm, calculate the total cost.</p></li>
                <li><p>Compare your design with classmates and discuss which design is most cost-effective.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

